<emphasis id="40B82727B965EC35EE7B59A57662D68E" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">H</emphasis>
) views showing variations of leaf lobes and colour in a single small population.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="1FCF92DF3E99C4BBBE388294265E7B39" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName id="AE3A18E8F1104C0F3BDE004EE501FF0A" authorityName="Hance, J. Bot. 21: 203, 1883 (Hance" authorityYear="1883" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia circumlobata" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="circumlobata">
<emphasis id="285891ECFDD35EFABD02957407D2F785" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Begonia circumlobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
displays significant variation in plant size, morphology of leaves, and flowers (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A150A2A38AFA7B395314C8F2EA45DF48" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Begonia lipingensis and B. circumlobata (E-H photos by Daike Tian) A-E Begonia lipingensis: A holotype (WU) (digitalised by Herbarium of Institut fur Botanik der Universitat Wien) B close-up view of type leaf C close-up of male flower from holotype, showing abaxial hairs on the middle of outer tepals D wild blooming plants E, F male flowers showing colour variation G, H Begonia circumlobata: adaxial (G) and abaxial (H) views showing variations of leaf lobes and colour in a single small population." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.153.50805.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/432247" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">3E-H</figureCitation>
). The leaves may be shallowly to very deeply lobed in the same population, even for the same individual and very few of the plants are shallowly double-lobed like 
<taxonomicName id="1E845CC03BE21A2B5FA815CC0E3454E6" genus="B." lsidName="B. jinyunensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="jinyunensis">
<emphasis id="092296D89FB308D2BFB7C1F2C69B3F97" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">B. jinyunensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
C.I Peng, B.Ding &amp; Q.Wang (
<bibRefCitation id="38EF7EB687616694971B6CD78106B6AF" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1186/s40529-014-0062-6" author="Ding, B" journalOrPublisher="Botanical Studies (Taipei, Taiwan)" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" pagination="62 - 69" refId="B9" refString="Ding, B, Nakamura, K, Kono, Y, Ho, MJ, Peng, CI, 2014. Begonia jinyunensis (Begoniaceae,section Platycentrum), a new palmately compound leaved species from Chongqing, China. Botanical Studies (Taipei, Taiwan) 55 (1): 62 - 69, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1186/s40529-014-0062-6" title="Begonia jinyunensis (Begoniaceae, section Platycentrum), a new palmately compound leaved species from Chongqing, China." url="https://doi.org/10.1186/s40529-014-0062-6" volume="55" year="2014">Ding et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7D7A33A6EDA7FCB9920456A6E8B0848C" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Begonia lipingensis and B. circumlobata (E-H photos by Daike Tian) A-E Begonia lipingensis: A holotype (WU) (digitalised by Herbarium of Institut fur Botanik der Universitat Wien) B close-up view of type leaf C close-up of male flower from holotype, showing abaxial hairs on the middle of outer tepals D wild blooming plants E, F male flowers showing colour variation G, H Begonia circumlobata: adaxial (G) and abaxial (H) views showing variations of leaf lobes and colour in a single small population." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.153.50805.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/432247" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">3G, H</figureCitation>
). The leaves of most plants are pure green on two sides, while others may have deep green leaves with abxially red surface. Occasionally, variegated plants with white-spotted leaves could be seen in some populations such as in Huangsang National Nature Reserve of Suining, Hunan Province. Flowers can be white, whitish-pink, pink or nearly red (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="77F3B47C23EDB2A1B4F002828FF0A333" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Begonia lipingensis and B. circumlobata (E-H photos by Daike Tian) A-E Begonia lipingensis: A holotype (WU) (digitalised by Herbarium of Institut fur Botanik der Universitat Wien) B close-up view of type leaf C close-up of male flower from holotype, showing abaxial hairs on the middle of outer tepals D wild blooming plants E, F male flowers showing colour variation G, H Begonia circumlobata: adaxial (G) and abaxial (H) views showing variations of leaf lobes and colour in a single small population." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.153.50805.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/432247" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">3D, E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3ED7DDA47A2C755BC14EC2F66F1C125" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="D2F70C9757F6D79E538623ACD538FFEB" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Distribution and phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D48BCE4F1B0FA1769CBD017A8188CA23" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName id="E120968145E268AC2699CE6F5ABF01F9" authorityName="Hance, J. Bot. 21: 203, 1883 (Hance" authorityYear="1883" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia circumlobata" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="circumlobata">
<emphasis id="2D7D6CD27C789C92FA5706140C02EA12" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Begonia circumlobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in at least seven provinces of China, from western Hubei to Hunan, Jiangxi, Fujian, Guangdong, Guangxi and Guizhou, growing on flat areas, steep slopes or rock surfaces along or near stream and valley. Alt. 200-1230 m (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1167E1C1923F77188B8A165B2A5D6633" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Distribution map of B. circumlobata (including syn. B. lipingensis) Triangles show distribution based on specimens and field surveys and red triangles indicate type locality of B. circumlobata (Guangdong) and B. lipingensis (Guizhou), respectively." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.153.50805.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/432248" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">4</figureCitation>
). Flowering June to September, fruiting July to October.
</paragraph>
<caption id="E62A9F8ED41663E4DE3F907259316A70" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.153.50805.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/432248" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" start="Figure 4" startId="F4">
<paragraph id="06C56CF4DC6A3FB0224CFB0F36E78764" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="FDABBCD737E8F78D05EA67904488FABC" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Figure 4.</emphasis>
Distribution map of 
<taxonomicName id="B3A03BCFE55321BD1813A13667534CD5" genus="B." lsidName="B. circumlobata" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="circumlobata">
<emphasis id="48301932217DAD8378FA782D1BEDE717" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">B. circumlobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(including syn. 
<taxonomicName id="A4C549536331A2E33A3797F54167D954" genus="B." lsidName="B. lipingensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="lipingensis">
<emphasis id="CE2C4068527AB49F16FACD93345C01FB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">B. lipingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) Triangles show distribution based on specimens and field surveys and red triangles indicate type locality of 
<taxonomicName id="C519ADC2D160F4CAAA04F040C769E30B" genus="B." lsidName="B. circumlobata" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="circumlobata">
<emphasis id="40CBA914D99ADE64D9208A83B9483626" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">B. circumlobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Guangdong) and 
<taxonomicName id="05D44EB4055882A3166A0BEE0CF87FD2" genus="B." lsidName="B. lipingensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="lipingensis">
<emphasis id="70D55B7588704A9C86A74E9E3272FE33" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">B. lipingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Guizhou), respectively.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3DB0BD6DCFD2748F47D0A3E4BAEF4E56" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" type="conservation status">
<paragraph id="A0038F792101CA0C53A4B9ABBC7F62B7" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9F78E2603EF74C5053AD63B81533793D" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Least Concern (LC) due to wide distribution and usually large populations. However, in some places, a small number of plants with variegated leaves (adaxially white spots) have high value as ornamentals. Therefore, these variegated individuals may be over-collected by humans.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7E3E02FD253DC4D83DA0157C1854A7CA" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="39A2CE9EB2E9DDAB0C47A275D35FFFAD" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3F0C366C1600F0FF6BD4D5F83DA3A689" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName id="3F8BC27FDEE9B84B8F252733094A1C02" authorityName="Hance, J. Bot. 21: 203, 1883 (Hance" authorityYear="1883" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia circumlobata" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="circumlobata">
<emphasis id="72F5548F4CF81FA49AC28DE168AB9029" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Begonia circumlobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has sparsely hairy leaf blades and outer tepals of male flowers (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A8C94A5746151D0260081C2D9F25CD92" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Begonia lipingensis and B. circumlobata (E-H photos by Daike Tian) A-E Begonia lipingensis: A holotype (WU) (digitalised by Herbarium of Institut fur Botanik der Universitat Wien) B close-up view of type leaf C close-up of male flower from holotype, showing abaxial hairs on the middle of outer tepals D wild blooming plants E, F male flowers showing colour variation G, H Begonia circumlobata: adaxial (G) and abaxial (H) views showing variations of leaf lobes and colour in a single small population." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.153.50805.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/432247" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">3C</figureCitation>
). It is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="DEC37987FDE75CD91827DBD7266361A0" genus="B." lsidName="B. jinyunensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="jinyunensis">
<emphasis id="1A103A155288FD735C9216166EF7F874" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">B. jinyunensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="EF29562901642A869B6554FCCF9DF88F" genus="B." lsidName="B. laminariae" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="laminariae">
<emphasis id="7D1535F56A357659FCA8414AFDDB1DBF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">B. laminariae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, particularly in the morphology of its leaves, flowers and fruits. 
<taxonomicName id="C496F309D4E4C6E8D5627E8811780EEB" authorityName="Hance, J. Bot. 21: 203, 1883 (Hance" authorityYear="1883" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia circumlobata" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="circumlobata">
<emphasis id="41E06180F94FA27467275893FA202783" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Begonia circumlobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also easily confused with some individuals of 
<taxonomicName id="8A88350A0840C926C5941E0B5C27A6A7" genus="B." lsidName="B. pedatifida" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="pedatifida">
<emphasis id="1EB80B18FC41770F95F143CC628F2171" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">B. pedatifida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="3685EC4EE91C3D1C065649DCABC5E528" originalValue="Lév">Lev</normalizedToken>
. (
<bibRefCitation id="C2E7DCFC295DB4B91F2F4F607C7E894F" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/fedr.19090070108" author="Leveille, H" journalOrPublisher="Repertorium Specierum Novarum Regni Vegetabilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" pagination="20 - 23" refId="B28" refString="Leveille, H, 1909. Decades plantarum novarum XVI, in Fedde. Repertorium Specierum Novarum Regni Vegetabilis 7 (1-3): 20 - 23, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1002/fedr.19090070108" title="Decades plantarum novarum XVI, in Fedde." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/fedr.19090070108" volume="7" year="1909">
<normalizedToken id="3E75A13197EA03F6A4458A486EE9632D" originalValue="Léveillé">Leveille</normalizedToken>
1909
</bibRefCitation>
), particularly when examining herbarium specimens. Unpublished morphological and molecular data (Tian et al.) suggests that 
<taxonomicName id="7A30112FB7C103FA713B1782AC9FF528" genus="B." lsidName="B. jinyunensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="jinyunensis">
<emphasis id="75E73C6BB5102F8DE628269107929B56" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">B. jinyunensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be treated as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="DB8A7FAF9E9CBC525583F4086E8774AF" genus="B." lsidName="B. circumlobata" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="circumlobata">
<emphasis id="E848B3DF88BED53501609F55AC86887B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">B. circumlobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. At the same time, a study is ongoing concerning the taxonomic relationship of 
<taxonomicName id="F82049529B73184AC0A3FBF76B267571" genus="B." lsidName="B. circumlobata" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="circumlobata">
<emphasis id="5C2FB4A83F9604AF5FF96F81FEE69CCE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">B. circumlobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A643A9C0F817D4230B6F0D29B84CB349" genus="B." lsidName="B. laminariae" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="laminariae">
<emphasis id="9A52BFB210DBA7ADD08B8EE3A8E2DA87" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">B. laminariae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Irmsch. (
<bibRefCitation id="B7D84BAA8BD893AA07E91BACA72244A8" author="Irmscher, E" journalOrPublisher="Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" pagination="35 - 45" refId="B24" refString="Irmscher, E, 1951. Some new Chinese species of Begonia. Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh 21 (1): 35 - 45" title="Some new Chinese species of Begonia." volume="21" year="1951">Irmscher 1951</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="D8DF86EF8049C972697951150339EDF4" genus="B." lsidName="B. pedatifida" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="pedatifida">
<emphasis id="E6B09832164CCA9E69F7F01240788635" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">B. pedatifida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Since plants with intermediate morphology amongst these three taxa exist in the wild, it appears that gene flow or natural hybridisation might occur between them.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
